has been exerci&s;ed in every age; and an infinite num|ber of &s;y&s;tems have
been the re&s;ult. That of Shafte&s;|bury, in which he e&s;tabli&s;hes a
natural &s;en&s;e of mo+ral beauty, was originally profe&s;&s;ed by Plato, and
only adorned by the Engli&s;h philo&s;opher. Thi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="OXF" EXTENT="1 letter"> &s;eemed to be the age of &s;peculation. Berkeley,
